    "statement": "Compute the convergents of the continued fraction\n$\\displaystyle [0;1,2,3,4]$.", 
    "year": 2009, 
    "sols": [
        "A convergent is given by\n\n$\\displaystyle [a_{0};a_{1},a_{2},...,a_{n}] = \\frac{h_{n}}{k_{n}}$\n\nwhere we also have the recurrence relations\n\n\\begin{align*}\nh_{n} &= a_{n}h_{n-1} + h_{n-2}\\\\\nk_{n} &= a_{n}k_{n-1} + k_{n-2}\n\\end{align*}\n\nsubject to the initial conditions\n$\\displaystyle h_{-1} = 1, h_{-2} = 0, k_{-1} = 0, k_{-2} = 1$.\n\nPlugging in our values, we see that\n\n\\begin{align*}\nh_{0} &= a_{0}h_{0-1} + h_{0-2} = (0)(1) + 0 = 0\\\\\nk_{0} &= a_{0}k_{0-1} + k_{0-2} = (0)(0) + 1 = 1\\\\\nh_{1} &= a_{1}h_{1-1} + h_{1-2} = (1)(0) + 1 = 1\\\\\nk_{1} &= a_{1}k_{1-1} + k_{1-2} = (1)(1) + 0 = 1\\\\\nh_{2} &= a_{2}h_{2-1} + h_{2-2} = (2)(1) + 0 = 2\\\\\nk_{2} &= a_{2}k_{2-1} + k_{2-2} = (2)(1) + 1 = 3\\\\\nh_{3} &= a_{3}h_{3-1} + h_{3-2} = (3)(2) + 1 = 7\\\\\nk_{3} &= a_{3}k_{3-1} + k_{3-2} = (3)(3) + 1 = 10\\\\\nh_{4} &= a_{4}h_{4-1} + h_{4-2} = (4)(7) + 2 = 30\\\\\nk_{4} &= a_{4}k_{4-1} + k_{4-2} = (4)(10) + 3 = 43\n\\end{align*}\n\nThus the convergents are\n\n$\\displaystyle \\left\\{0,1,\\frac{2}{3},\\frac{7}{10},\\frac{30}{43} \\right\\}$"
    ], 
    "hints": [
        "Recall the notation and terminology. A convergent is given by\n\n$\\displaystyle [a_{0};a_{1},a_{2},...,a_{n}] = \\frac{h_{n}}{k_{n}}$\n\nwhere we also have the recurrence relations\n\n\\begin{align*}\nh_{n} &= a_{n}h_{n-1} + h_{n-2}\\\\\nk_{n} &= a_{n}k_{n-1} + k_{n-2}\n\\end{align*}\n\nsubject to the initial conditions\n$\\displaystyle h_{-1} = 1, h_{-2} = 0, k_{-1} = 0, k_{-2} = 1$."
